snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like the analogy between the talking cat plot and audience discourse is a bit unclear,
because the cat's arguments are disingenuous - the cat says "don't ask questions" because "the point is to have fun" and "no answer would be satisfying", but his real motivation is selfish: he's trying to avoid the revelation of the truth about him because he's ashamed of it (as he later admits to the dragon).
And Rick may be unhappy with the truth, but that doesn't mean he regrets learning it, because for him it wasn't about getting a "satisfying" answer, it was about answering a question that needed to be answered, it didn't matter if the truth made anyone "happy".
So if the cat is a selfish liar hiding a dark secret and Rick calls him out in it, isn't the show actually siding with Rick?

snippet.textDisplay:
Student: "Sir, can I ask a question?"

Teacher: "Yes!"

Student: "How do you put an elephant inside a fridge?"

Teacher: "I don't know."

Student: "It's easy, you just open the fridge and put it in. I have another question!"

Teacher: "Ok, ask."

Student: "How to put a donkey inside the fridge?"

Teacher: "It's easy, you just open the fridge and put it in."

Student: "No sir, You just open the fridge take out the elephant and put it in." Teacher: "Ooh...ok!!"

Student: "Let me ask another one. If all the animals went to the lion's birthday party, and one animal went missing which one would it be?"

Teacher: "The lion of course! Because it wud eat all the animals."

Student: "No sir, it is the donkey becoz it's still inside the fridge."

Teacher: "Are you kidding me?"

Student: "No sir, 1 last question."

Teacher: "Ok!"

Student: "If there's a river full of crocodiles and you wanted to cross, how would you?"

Teacher: "There's no way, I would need a boat to cross."

Student: "No sir, you just swim and cross it because all the animals went to the lion's birthday party..."

Teacher: "I have my own question, if all the students come to school except one person, who is the person..."

Student: "No idea sir..."

Teacher: "It's you because you are on two weeks suspension."

snippet.textDisplay: Couldn't it be that the cat is living concept of the paradox of "Schrodinger's Cat"? The idea of asking questions on whether the cat is alive or dead inside a sealed box and the only way to know is to open said box and learn the truth whether we like it or not, or whether its best to let things be left unanswered in case we fear that same answer. What Jerry and Rick saw is that same paradox of what it is that they don't know and question and now see it as whether they should of known in the first place. Similar to when people try to prevent accepting things by saying "Okay, Too much information"?
